{{notability|date=November 2011}} {{infobox weapon | name = K-15 Krajina | image = K-15 Krajina Missile.jpg | image_size = 300px | caption = K-15 Krajina Missile in 1995. | origin = {{Flagicon_image|Flag of Serbian Krajina (1991).svg}} [[Republic of Serbian Krajina|Serbian Krajina]] | type = [[Tactical ballistic missile]] | is_missile = yes | service = 1995 | used_by = {{Flagicon_image|War Flag of Serbian Krajina.svg}} [[Army of the Republic of Serb Krajina|Army of Serbian Krajina]] | wars = [[Yugoslav Wars]] | | designer = | design_date = | manufacturer = | unit_cost = | production_date = | number = | | weight = 5,100lb (2,300kg) | length = | width = | height = | diameter = | | filling = HE 1,001lb (454kg) | filling_weight = | detonation = | yield = | | engine = [[Liquid-propellant rocket|Liquid-propellant]] | engine_power = | fuel_capacity = | speed = | vehicle_range = 150km (93mi)<ref name=srps>[http://cns.miis.edu/npr/pdfs/31miss.pdf ''Ballistic, Cruise Missile, and Missile Defense Systems: Trade and Significant Developments, March 1995 - June 1995''] The Non-Proliferation Review, Fall 1995</ref> | guidance = [[Inertial navigation system|Inertial navigation]] | | wingspan = | propellant = | ceiling = | altitude = | depth = | boost = | accuracy = | launch_platform = | transport = [[ZIL 131]] }} The '''K-15 Krajina''' was a [[tactical ballistic missile]] displayed in [[Republic of Serbian Krajina]] in June 1995. It appeared to be a modified [[Soviet Navy]] [[P-15 Termit]] [[Anti-ship missile]] which was converted for use as a [[ballistic missile]] mounted on a [[S-75 Dvina]] launcher.<ref name=srps/>
The range was estimated to be 150km (93mi).<ref name=kraj>[http://www.missilethreat.com/missilesoftheworld/id.60/missile_detail.asp Duncan, Lennox, ''Ballistic Missiles'', Jane’s Defence Weekly, 17 April 1996] {{dead link|date=September 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> The extremely limited range of the K-15 Krajina, combined with what is presumed to be a small payload, made the threat from such a weapon minimal.<ref name=kraj/> Sources suggest that the missile development was continued by [[Republic of Serbia (1992–2006)|Serbia]] and [[Republic of Montenegro (1992–2006)|Montenegro]] well into 1996.<ref name=kraj/>
